DateReviewed: 2026-01-06
Description: Today's article will deal with Vault agent injector for Kubernetes, a way to deliver secrets to pods. We start with why we might want to use this (no hardcoded creds), and talk a bit about advantages, like that it is auditable and supports dynamic secrets that expire and rotate. It has a few moving parts - an init container to do initial auth and fetch the secrets; a sidecar to refresh secrets as needed; and a shared mem volume to store the secrets. We then do a multi-step walk through, setting up the vault for use with a K8s cluster. It's a 7 step process, with lots of configs and screenshots to help you follow the explaination.
BottomLine: Good walk through and background on Vault, a Kubernetes secret solution
